A020514.name: a(n) = 1^n + 2^n + 4^n + 8^n + 16^n.

The e.g.f.'s of A020554 (S(x)) and A014500 (U(x)) are related by S(x) = U(e^x-1).

E.g.f.: exp(-3/2+exp(x)/2)*Sum(exp(binomial(n+1, 2)*x)/n!, n=0..infinity) [probably in the Labelle paper] - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 27 2004

A020556.name: Number of oriented multigraphs on n labeled arcs (without loops).

A020557.name: Number of oriented multigraphs on n labeled arcs (with loops).

A020558.name: Number of ordered multigraphs on n labeled edges (without loops).

A020559.name: Number of ordered multigraphs on n labeled edges (with loops).

A020560.name: Number of ordered oriented multigraphs on n labeled arcs (without loops).

a((2n+1)*2^m) = A086592(n), m >= 0, n > 0. For n = 0 A086592(0) = 1 is needed. - _Yosu Yurramendi_, Feb 14 2017
a(4n+2) = a(4n+1) - a(4n) = a(2n+1) = a(4n+1) - a(n), n > 0. - _Yosu Yurramendi_, May 08 2018

A020665.name: a(n) is the (conjectured) maximal exponent k such that n^k does not contain a digit zero in its decimal expansion.
formula: a(10n) = 0 for any n>0. - _M. F. Hasler_, Dec 17 2014
a(100n+1) = 0 for any n>0. - _Robert Israel_, Apr 01 2015
a(80*n+65) <= 3, because for k >= 4, (80*n+65)^k == 625 mod 10000. - _Robert Israel_, Apr 02 2015
The following values and bounds are for the actual maximal exponents (not conjectured).

A020666.name: a(n)^n is the least n-th power containing every digit.

A020667.name: Least n-th power containing every digit.

A020668.name: Numbers of the form x^2 + 4*y^2.
formula: Complement of A097269 in A001481. - _Jean-Christophe Hervé_, Oct 25 2015

A020669.name: Numbers of form x^2 + 5 y^2.
formula: List contains 0 and all positive n such that 2*A035170(n) = A028586(2n) is nonzero. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 21 2006

A020696.name: Let a,b,c,...k be all divisors of n; a(n) = (a+1)*(b+1)*...*(k+1).

A020698.name: a(n) = 5*a(n-1) - 2*a(n-2), with a(0)=2, a(1)=9.
formula: a(k-1) = [M^k]_1,3, where M is the 3 X 3 matrix [2,1,2; 1,1,1; 2,1,2]. - _Simone Severini_, Jun 12 2006

If p[i]=Fibonacci(2i+1) and if A is the Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n-1)= det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 08 2010

A020699.name: Expansion of (1-3*x)/(1-5*x).
formula: a(n) = sum{k=0..n, C(n-1, k)*(Jac(2n-2k)+Jac(2n-2k-1))}+0^n/2, where Jac(n)=A001045(n). - _Paul Barry_, Jun 07 2005
a(0)=1, a(1)=2, a(n) = 5*a(n-1) for n>=2. [_Vincenzo Librandi_, Jan 01 2011]

A020700.name: Sum of n plus its prime factors = sum of n+1 plus its prime factors.

A020703.name: Take the sequence of natural numbers (A000027) and reverse successive subsequences of lengths 1,3,5,7,...
formula: a(n)=a(n-1)-1, if a(n-1)-1 > 0 is not in the set {a(k)| 1<=k<n}, else a(n)=m^2, where m^2 is the least square not yet in the sequence.
a(n+1)=(sqrt(a(n)-1)+2)^2, if a(n)-1 is a square, a(n+1)=a(n)-1, else.

A020704.name: Pisot sequences E(3,10), P(3,10).
formula: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) + a(n-2) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).
Theorem: For E(3,10), a(n) = 3 a(n - 1) +  a(n - 2) for n>=2. Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger, and implies the above conjectures. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 09 2016

A020707.name: Pisot sequences E(4,8), L(4,8), P(4,8), T(4,8).

A020708.name: Pisot sequences E(4,9), P(4,9).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-3) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).
Theorem: E(4,9) satisfies a(n) = 2 a(n - 1) + a(n - 3) for n >= 3. Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger, and implies the above conjectures. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 09 2016

A020709.name: Pisot sequence E(4,10).
formula: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - 2*a(n-2) + 2*a(n-3) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).
Theorem: a(n) = 3 a(n - 1) - 2 a(n - 2) + 2 a(n - 3) for n>=3. Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger, and implies the above conjectures. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 09 2016

A020711.name: Pisot sequences E(5,7), P(5,7).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) - a(n-4) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).

Theorem: E(5,7) satisfies a(n) = 3 a(n - 1) + 2 a(n - 2) + a(n - 3) - a(n - 4) for n >= 4. Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger, and implies the above conjectures. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 09 2016
Empirical formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-3) - 1. - _Greg Dresden_, May 18 2020

A020713.name: Pisot sequences E(5,9), P(5,9).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).

Theorem: E(5,9) satisfies a(n) = 2 a(n - 1) -  a(n - 2) + a(n - 3) for n>=3. Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger, and implies the above conjectures. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 09 2016

A020714.name: a(n) = 5 * 2^n.
formula: If m is a term greater than 5 of this sequence then m = 5*phi(phi(m)). - _Farideh Firoozbakht_, Aug 16 2005
a(n) = A118416(n+1,3) for n>2. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 27 2006
a(n) = A173786(n+2,n) for n > 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 28 2010

A020716.name: Pisot sequences E(6,8), P(6,8).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) - a(n-4) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).

Theorem: E(6,8) satisfies a(n) = a(n - 1) + a(n - 2) - a(n - 4) for n>=4. Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger. This shows that the above conjectures are correct. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 10 2016

A020718.name: Pisot sequences E(6,10), P(6,10).
formula: Theorem: E(6,10) satisfies a(n) = 2 a(n - 1) - a(n - 3) + a(n - 5) - a(n - 6) for n >= 6. Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger. This shows that the above conjectures are correct. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 10 2016

A020720.name: Pisot sequences E(7,9), P(7,9).
formula: a(n) = a(n-2) + a(n-3) for n>=3. (Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger.) - N. J. A. Sloane, Sep 09 2016

A020721.name: Pisot sequences E(7,10), P(7,10).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) - a(n-4) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).

Theorem: E(7,10) satisfies  a(n) = 2 a(n - 1) - a(n - 2) + a(n - 3) - a(n - 4) for n>=4. Proved using the PtoRv program of Ekhad-Sloane-Zeilberger. This shows that the above conjectures are correct. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 10 2016
Empirical formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-3) - 1. - _Greg Dresden_, May 18 2020

A020726.name: Expansion of 1/((1-6*x)*(1-10*x)*(1-11*x)).
formula: a(n) = 21*a(n-1) - 110*a(n-2) + 6^n for n>1, a(0)=1, a(1)=27. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Mar 11 2011

In general, for the expansion of 1/((1-r*x)(1-s*x)(1-t*x)) with t > s > r, we have the formula: a(n) = ((s-r)*t^(n+2) - (t-r)*s^(n+2) + (t-s)*r^(n+2))/((s-r)*(t-r)*(t-s)). - _Yahia Kahloune_, Sep 09 2013

A020727.name: Pisot sequence P(2,7): a(0)=2, a(1)=7, thereafter a(n+1) is the nearest integer to a(n)^2/a(n-1).

A020728.name: Pisot sequence T(2,9), a(n) = floor(a(n-1)^2/a(n-2)).
formula: Pisot sequence T(x, y): a(0) = x, a(1) = y, a(n) = floor(a(n-1)^2/a(n-2)).

formula: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - 3*a(n-2) + 2*a(n-3) - a(n-4) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).

A020738.name: Consider number of divisors of binomial(n, k), k=0..n; a(n) = multiplicity of maximal value.

A020746.name: Pisot sequence T(3,7), a(n) = floor(a(n-1)^2/a(n-2)).
formula: I believe that David Boyd has proved that this g.f. is correct. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Aug 11 2016

A020748.name: Pisot sequence T(4,10), a(n) = floor(a(n-1)^2/a(n-2)).
formula: Note the warning in A010925 from Pab Ter (pabrlos(AT)yahoo.com), May 23 2004: [A010925] and other examples show that it is essential to reject conjectured generating functions for Pisot sequences until a proof or reference is provided. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jul 26 2016

A020749.name: Pisot sequence T(5,8), a(n) = floor(a(n-1)^2/a(n-2)).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) - a(n-4) (holds at least up to n = 1000 but is not known to hold in general).

Note the warning in A010925 from Pab Ter (pabrlos(AT)yahoo.com), May 23 2004: [A010925] and other examples show that it is essential to reject conjectured generating functions for Pisot sequences until a proof or reference is provided. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jul 26 2016

A020750.name: Pisot sequence T(5,9), a(n) = floor(a(n-1)^2/a(n-2)).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - 2*a(n-4) + a(n-5) (holds at least up to n = 40000 but is not known to hold in general).

A020756.name: Numbers that are the sum of two triangular numbers.
formula: Numbers n such that 4n+1 is the sum of two squares, i.e. such that 4n+1 is in A001481. Hence n is a member if and only if 4n+1 = odd square * product of distinct primes of form 4k+1. (Fred Helenius and others, Dec 18 2004)

Equivalently, we may say that a positive integer n can be partitioned into a sum of two triangular numbers if and only if every 4 k + 3 prime factor in the canonical form of 4 n + 1 occurs with an even exponent. - _Ant King_, Nov 29 2010
Also, the values of n for which 8n+2 can be partitioned into a sum of two squares of natural numbers. - _Ant King_, Nov 29 2010
Closed under the operation f(x, y) = 4*x*y + x + y.

A020757.name: Numbers that are not the sum of two triangular numbers.

A020758.name: Expansion of 1/((1-6x)(1-10x)(1-12x)).
formula: a(n) = 22*a(n-1) - 120*a(n-2) + 6^n for n>1, a(0)=1, a(1)=28. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Mar 11 2011

A020759.name: Decimal expansion of (-1)*Gamma'(1/2)/Gamma(1/2) where Gamma(x) denotes the Gamma function.
formula: Gamma'(1/2)/Gamma(1/2) = -EulerGamma - 2*log(2) = -1.9635100260214234794... where EulerGamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant (A001620).

A020760.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(3).
formula: Equals cosine of the magic angle: cos(A195696). - _Stanislav Sykora_, Mar 07 2016
Equals square root of A010701. - _Michel Marcus_, Mar 07 2016

A020761.name: Decimal expansion of 1/2.
formula: -zeta(0), zeta being the Riemann function. - _Stanislav Sykora_, Mar 27 2014
a(0) = 5; a(n) = 0, n > 0. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Mar 27 2014

A020762.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(5).
formula: Equals lim_{n -> infinity} A000045(n)/A000032(n). - _Bruno Berselli_, Jan 22 2018

A020765.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(8).
formula: Equals A201488 minus 1/2. Equals 1/(A010487-4) minus 1/4. - _Jon E. Schoenfield_, Jan 09 2017

A020767.name: Product_{k=1..n} b(k), where b(k) = binary expansion of k (A007088) but read as if it were a decimal number.

A020777.name: Decimal expansion of (-1)*Gamma'(1/4)/Gamma(1/4) where Gamma(x) denotes the Gamma function.
formula: Gamma'(1/4)/Gamma(1/4) = -EulerGamma - 3*log(2) - Pi/2 where EulerGamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant (A001620).
Pi = gamma(0,1/4) - gamma(0,3/4) = A020777 - A200134, where gamma(n,x) denotes the generalized Stieltjes constants. - _Peter Luschny_, May 16 2018

A020782.name: Expansion of 1/((1-7x)(1-8x)(1-9x)).
formula: If we define f(m,j,x)=sum(binomial(m,k)*stirling2(k,j)*x^(m-k),k=j..m) then a(n-2)=f(n,2,7), (n>=2). - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 26 2009

A020784.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(27).
formula: Equals Sum_{k>=0} binomial(2*k,k) * k/16^k. - _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 02 2020

A020797.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(40).
formula: Equals Re(sqrt(5*i)/10) = Im(sqrt(5*i)/10). - _Karl V. Keller, Jr._, Sep 01 2020

A020825.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(68).
formula: A020774 divided by 2. - _R. J. Mathar_, Aug 28 2013

A020829.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(72) = 1/(3*2^(3/2)) = sqrt(2)/12.
formula: Equals Integral_{x=0..Pi/4} sin(x)^2 * cos(x) dx. - _Amiram Eldar_, May 31 2021

A020832.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(75).
formula: (csc(Pi/3))/10, where csc is the cosecant function. - _Alonso del Arte_, Apr 30 2012
Product_{n>=1} ((3*n+1)/(3*n+2))^((-1)^n)), with offset 1. (see Hu link). - _Michel Marcus_, Jun 02 2015

A020837.name: Decimal expansion of 1/sqrt(80) = sqrt(5)/20.
formula: Equals 1/sqrt(80) = sqrt(5)/20 = (-1 + 2*phi)/20, with phi from A001622.

A020868.name: Number of single component edge-subgraphs in Moebius ladder M_n.
formula: G.f.: see G in the Maple program. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Dec 21 2004

A020869.name: Number of single component forests in Moebius ladder M_n.
formula: The McSorley reference gives the approximation a(n) ~ 0.8757*n*4.3652^n - 1.5432*n*0.4786^n*cos(0.8458*n+0.9674) + n^2 - 2*n. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Dec 21 2004

A020870.name: Number of strong single-component edge-subgraphs in Moebius ladder M_n.

A020871.name: Number of spanning trees in a Moebius ladder M_n with 2n vertices.

A020872.name: Number of restricted forests in Moebius ladder M_n.
formula: For large n, (4.8820)^n < a(n) < (6.4188)^n (Th. 10.1.). - C. Ronaldo (aga_new_ac(AT)hotmail.com), Jan 17 2005
a(n) is asymptotic to c^n where c = 6.349088... is the inverse of the root of x^4 - x^3 - 4 x^2 + 7 x - 1 of smallest modulus. - _Peter Kagey_, May 10 2019

A020873.name: a(n) = number of cycles in Moebius ladder M_n.

A020874.name: Number of paths in Moebius ladder M_n.

A020875.name: Number of (undirected) Hamiltonian paths in n-Moebius ladder.
formula: If n is even, a(n) = n^3+2*n, else a(n) = n^3+3*n.

A020876.name: a(n) = ((5+sqrt(5))/2)^n + ((5-sqrt(5))/2)^n.
formula: Also, a(n) = (sqrt(5)*phi)^n + (sqrt(5)/phi)^n, where phi = golden ratio. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Aug 08 2014
Let S(n, m)=sum(k=0, n, binomial(n, k)*fibonacci(m*k)), then for n>0 a(n)= S(2*n, 2)/S(n, 2). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 22 2003
Binomial transform of A005248. - _Carl Najafi_, Sep 10 2011

A020877.name: Number of matchings in Moebius ladder M_n.
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 4*a(n-2) - a(n-4). - _Eric W. Weisstein_, Oct 03 2017 [Corrected by _Altug Alkan_, Apr 06 2018]
The McSorley reference gives the approximation a(n)~(3.2143)^n+(-0.6751)^n+(0.4608)^n-(-1)^n. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Dec 21 2004

A020878.name: Number of maximum matchings in the n-Moebius ladder M_n.
formula: If n mod 2 = 0 then L(n) else L(n)+2, where L() are the Lucas numbers.
a(n) = ((1 - sqrt(5))/2)^n + ((1 + sqrt(5))/2)^n for n even.

A020879.name: Number of elementary edge-subgraphs in Moebius ladder M_n.

A020880.name: Number of strong elementary edge-subgraphs in Moebius ladder M_n.

A020881.name: Number of strong restricted edge-subgraphs in Moebius ladder M_n.
formula: For large n, (3.2143)^n < a(n) < (6.4188)^n (Th. 23.1.) - C. Ronaldo (aga_new_ac(AT)hotmail.com), Jan 17 2005

A020914.name: Number of digits in the base-2 representation of 3^n.
formula: A098294(n) = a(n) + n for n > 0. - _Mike Winkler_, Dec 31 2010
a(n) = A070939(A000244(n)) = length of n-th row in triangle A227048. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jun 30 2013
a(n) = 1 + floor(n*log_2(3)) = 1 + A056576(n) = 1 + floor(n*A020857). - _L. Edson Jeffery_, Dec 12 2014

A020917.name: Maximum number of K4's (complete 4 graphs) a graph can contain if it contains at most n distinct K3's (triangles).

A020918.name: Expansion of 1/(1-4*x)^(7/2).
formula: a(n) = binomial(n+3, 3)*A000984(n+3)/A000984(3), where A000984 are the central binomial coefficients. - _Wolfdieter Lang_
a(n) = Sum_{a+b+c+d+e+f+g=n} f(a)*f(b)*f(c)*f(d)*f(e)*f(f)*f(g) with f(n)=A000984(n). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 22 2004
Boas-Buck recurrence: a(n) = (14/n)*Sum_{k=0..n-1} 4^(n-k-1)*a(k), n >= 1, a(0) = 1. Proof from a(n) = A046521(n+3, 3). See a comment there. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Aug 10 2017

A020919.name: Partition numbers mod 11.
formula: a(n) = A000041(n) mod 11. - _Sean A. Irvine_, May 04 2019

A020920.name: Expansion of 1/(1-4*x)^(9/2).
formula: a(n) = binomial(n+4, 4)*A000984(n+4)/A000984(4), where A000984 are the central binomial coefficients. - _Wolfdieter Lang_
a(n) = Sum_{ a+b+c+d+e+f+g+h+i=n} f(a)*f(b)*f(c)*f(d)*f(e)*f(f)*f(g) *f(h)*f(i) with f(n)=A000984(n). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 22 2004
Boas-Buck recurrence: a(n) = (18/n)*Sum_{k=0..n-1} 4^(n-k-1)*a(k), n >= 1, a(0) = 1. Proof from a(n) = A046521(n+4, 4). See a comment there.

A020921.name: Triangle read by rows: T(m,n) = number of solutions to 1 <= a(1) < a(2) < ... < a(m) <= n, where gcd( a(1), a(2), ..., a(m), n) = 1.

A020922.name: Expansion of 1/(1-4*x)^(11/2).

A020923.name: Expansion of (1-4*x)^(11/2).

A020925.name: Expansion of (1-4*x)^(13/2).
formula: a(n) = (-2)^n * Product_{i=0..n-1} (13-2*i) / n! for n>0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 19 2008
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) - 2*(2*n-13)*a(n-1) = 0 for n>0. - _Bruno Berselli_, Jul 02 2018

A020931.name: Expansion of (1-4*x)^(19/2).

Boas-Buck recurrence: a(n) = (42/n)*Sum_{k=0..n-1} 4^(n-k-1)*a(k), n >= 1, a(0) = 1. Proof from a(n) = A046521(n+10, 10). See a comment there. - Wolfdieter Lang, Aug 10 2017

A020933.name: Expansion of (1-4*x)^(21/2).
formula: D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +2*(-2*n+23)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 17 2020

formula: Any number n has unique representation as a sum of terms from {1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 9, 13, 19, ...} (cf. A000930) such that no two terms are adjacent or pen-adjacent; e.g., 7=6+1. Sequence gives all n where that representation involves 1.
Conjecture: a(n) = A202342(n) + n. - _Sean A. Irvine_, May 05 2019

formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = 2*x + (1 + x + x^2) * A(x^2). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 08 2011

formula: a(n) = kn + O(log n) where k = 2 + sqrt(2) = 3.414213562.... - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Feb 27 2017

A020968.name: Expansion of 1/((1-7*x)*(1-8*x)*(1-11*x)).
formula: a(n) = 19*a(n-1) - 88*a(n-2) + 7^n for n>1, a(0)=1, a(1)=26. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Mar 15 2011

A020969.name: Expansion of 1/((1-7*x)*(1-8*x)*(1-12*x)).
formula: a(n) = 20*a(n-1) - 96*a(n-2) + 7^n for n>1, a(0)=1, a(1)=27. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Mar 15 2011

A020973.name: Expansion of 1/((1-7*x)*(1-10*x)*(1-11*x)).
formula: a(n) = 21*a(n-1) - 110*a(n-2) + 7^n for n>1, a(0)=1, a(1)=28. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Mar 15 2011

A020974.name: Expansion of 1/((1-7*x)*(1-10*x)*(1-12*x)).
formula: a(n) = 22*a(n-1) - 120*a(n-2) + 7^n for n>1 a(0)=1, a(1)=29. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Mar 15 2011

A020976.name: Expansion of 1/((1-8*x)*(1-9*x)*(1-10*x)).
formula: If we define f(m,j,x)=sum(binomial(m,k)*stirling2(k,j)*x^(m-k),k=j..m) then a(n-2)=f(n,2,8), (n>=2). - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 26 2009

A020982.name: Expansion of 1/((1-9*x)*(1-10*x)*(1-11*x)).
formula: If we define f(m,j,x) = Sum_{k=j..m} (binomial(m,k)*stirling2(k,j)*x^(m-k)) then a(n-2)=f(n,2,9), (n>=2). - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 26 2009

A020985.name: The Rudin-Shapiro or Golay-Rudin-Shapiro sequence (coefficients of the Shapiro polynomials).
formula: a(0) = 1, a(2n) = a(n), a(2n+1) = a(n) * (-1)^n. [Brillhart and Carlitz, in proof of theorem 4]
a(0) = a(1) = 1, a(2n) = a(n), a(2n+1) = a(n)*(1-2*(n AND 1)), where AND is the bitwise AND operator. - _Alex Ratushnyak_, May 13 2012
Brillhart and Morton (1978) list many properties.
Sum(n >= 1, a(n-1)(8n^2+4n+1)/(2n(2n+1)(4n+1)) = 1; see Allouche and Sondow, 2015. - _Jean-Paul Allouche_ and _Jonathan Sondow_, Mar 21 2015

A020986.name: a(n) = n-th partial sum of Golay-Rudin-Shapiro sequence A020985.
formula: Brillhart and Morton (1978) list many properties.

A020987.name: Zero-one version of Golay-Rudin-Shapiro sequence (or word).
